      "= 1`: `4 x + 1 = 17 ⇒ x = 4`, so `(4, 1, 1)` is fixed, also `(k, 1, 1)` for `k = 4`.\n   `y = 2`: `8 x + 4 = 17 ⇒ 8 x = 13` no. \n   `y = 3`: `12 x + 9 = 17`, `x = 8/12`, no. \n   So no other fixed points of form `(x, y, y)` in this case. \n\nBut perhaps another type of fixed points? Are there fixed points not of the form `(x, y, y)`?\n\nWe check above condition `(x, y, z) = (x - y + z, y, 2 y - z)`. So we deduced `y = z` and `z = y`, but this was assuming the entire triple is equal. But perhaps something is missing? Actually, for the involution to be fixed, we have:\n`secondInvo (x, y, z) = (x - y + z, y, 2 * y - z)`, if it must equal `(x, y, z)`, we get:\n   1. `x - y + z = x` ⇒ `z = y`\n   2. `2 * y - z = z` ⇒ `2 y = 2 z` ⇒ `z =",
